        </a>
      </div>

      <!-- Content -->
      <p>
        MIT is a <strong> minimal reimplementation of Git</strong> written entirely
        in C. The project was created to deeply understand Git internals, including
        object storage, references, commits, and repository structure.
      </p>

      <h2>Goals</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Understand how Git works under the hood</li>
        <li>Implement core Git commands from scratch</li>
        <li>Practice low-level systems programming in C</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Implemented Features</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><code>mit init</code> – repository initialization</li>
        <li><code>mit hash-object</code> – object creation</li>
        <li><code>mit cat-file</code> – object inspection</li>
        <li>Basic object storage (blobs, trees, commits)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tech Stack</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>C (C17)</li>
        <li>POSIX APIs</li>
        <li>Filesystem-based object storage</li>
      </ul>

    </article>
  </main>
